{
  "texts": [
    "For instance, GPT-4 [20], a highly advanced AI language model, has been observed to acquire skills such as programming, playing chess, and other complex tasks without being explicitly trained for them.",
    "These emergent capabilities can go unnoticed until they manifest during the AI system's operation, posing challenges for monitoring and predicting potential impacts.",
    "Some recent research has brought into question the emergent nature of such capabilities, arguing that in fact the relevant proto-capabilities already existed in smaller models [80], but this objection does not hold for capabilities we do not explicitly test for.Emergent properties of AI systems arise from the interaction between the AI system and its environment or from the system's internal dynamics.",
    "These properties are often difficult to predict and can lead to surprising capabilities that were not initially intended [94].",
    "Even when AI systems like large language models (LLMs) are closely monitored, they may still contain surprise capabilities that only become apparent during their operation."
  ]
}